Part 1¶


The Dataset : We are using the Ecoli Data Set which has 9 columns Sequence Name, mcg,gvh,lip,chg,aac,alm1,alm2 and Class. We will remove the sequence name as it is unique for each rows and which is not useful for our ML model. And we will perform the operations to predict the class variable. In the data cleaning method we will remove the class having instances less than 10 as given in the report.

Tasks¶

  1. Loading the dataset.
  2. Cleaning the data including removing classes having instances less than 10.
  3. Data visualization.
  4. Scale the X variable (independent variable).
  5. Make Decision Tree Classifer using GridSearchCV and get the Best Model out of it.
  6. Apply same classifier with scaled X variable.
  7. Comapre the results

Method for removing class¶

Here we will remove the classes having instances less than 10

In [6]:
def removeClass(file):
    x = file
    
    print(x['Class'].value_counts())
    print("--------------------------")
    
    #getting indexes 
    indexes = x['Class'].value_counts().index.values
    #values of index
    values =  x['Class'].value_counts().values
    l=[]
    #removing the number of instance of class less than 10
    print("We are removing the following classes given below as the number of instances are less than 10\n")
    for i in range(0,len(indexes)):
        if(values[i] < 10):
            l.append(indexes[i])
            indexNames = x[(x['Class'] == indexes[i])].index
            x.drop(indexNames , inplace=True)
            print(indexNames)
    print("\n---Class removed----")
    print(l)
    return x
y = removeClass(file)

  6. imU (inner membrane, uncleavable signal sequence) class has higher value when chg is 0.05
  7. The value of imU is higher when alm1 and alm2 is high.

Independent and dependent variables¶

Our dependent variable is Y which will be used to predict the output using our model and rest all the attributes will be the independent variables. While making the model using GridSearch we do not need to make the test set because the function itself will create the test set with it's fold which is cv.
cv=3 means the data will be divided into 3 sets and each set will be a test set once in each iteration, we will see it in the following step while making the classifer.

1. Decision tree Classifier¶

We are implementing the classifer with the raw value(unscaled) and then we make one more classifier with the scaled value in the next step.

Decision Tree Regressor¶

    1. max_depth = create nodes
    2. creation = gets the index value. gini or entropy
    3. min_sample_leaf= minimun leaf on each node

Unscaled¶

In [12]:
tree_clf = DecisionTreeClassifier()
param_grid={'max_depth': [2, 3, 4],'criterion': ['gini','entropy'],'min_samples_leaf': [1,2,3]}
gs=GridSearchCV(tree_clf,param_grid, cv=3)
gs.fit(X_train, dependent_variable)


Y_train_pred = cross_val_predict(gs, X_train, Y_train, cv=3)

best_params=gs.best_params_
accuracy=gs.best_score_

print("Best model",best_params)

Best model {'criterion': 'gini', 'max_depth': 4, 'min_samples_leaf': 3}

Explanation¶

The above Best Model consist of the best hyperparameters selected by the GridSearchCV from 3 folds. So, this says in 3 iteratation which are the best hyperparameters which generates the best output. best_patams_ provides the best hyperparameters for the model.

Scaled (feature scaling)¶

Why feature scaling? We are using feature scaling to get a proper euclidean distance which will help us to get a proper result for our model We will be using StandardScaler and use fit_transform() for feature selection fit_transform() will autometically transform the values after fitting it into our model.

We don't need to scale the Y value here.

Function for Regressor¶

Here we have to call the function thrice.

  1. First fucntion will be called for Decision Tree Regressor for unscaled data and will pass classifier name,input_variables,output_variables (unscaled) in this function.
  2. Second function will call the Decision Tree Regressor scaled data and will pass classifier name,input_variables,output_variables in this function. Here,the input_variable is scaled.
  3. Third function will call the Support Vactor Regressor for the scaled data and will pass classifier name,input_variables,output_variables in this function. Here, the input_variable is scaled.

To run the fucntion it is important to pass the right paramaters

In [43]:
def runPartTwo(classifier,input_variables,output_variables,scaled):
    
    if classifier == "DecisionTreeRegressor":            
        
        #CREATING TEST AND TRAIN SET
        X_train_p2 = input_variables
        Y_train_p2 = output_variables

        #1. Decision tree regressor
        tree_clf_p2 = DecisionTreeRegressor()
        param_grid={'max_depth': [2, 3, 4],'criterion':['mse'],'min_samples_leaf': [2, 3,4]}
        gs_p2=GridSearchCV(tree_clf_p2,param_grid, cv=3)
        gs_p2.fit(X_train_p2, Y_train_p2)
                
        
        
        if scaled == True :
            Y_pred_scaled_p2 = cross_val_predict(gs_p2, X_train_p2, Y_train_p2, cv=3)
            best_params_p2=gs_p2.best_params_ #FINDING BEST MODEL
            accuracy_p3=gs_p2.best_score_ #ACCURACY SCORE
            
            print("Decision Tree Regressor scaled")
            print("Best model:",best_params_p2)
            print("Mean squared error",mean_squared_error(Y_train_p2, Y_pred_scaled_p2))
            print("-----------------\n")
            
            plt.plot(Y_train_p2.to_numpy())
            plt.plot(Y_pred_scaled_p2)
            plt.legend(['Y', 'Y pred scaled'], loc=4)
            plt.show()
            
        else:
            Y_pred_p2 = cross_val_predict(gs_p2, X_train_p2, Y_train_p2, cv=3)
            best_params_p2=gs_p2.best_params_ #FINDING BEST MODEL
            accuracy_p3=gs_p2.best_score_ #ACCURACY SCORE
            
            print("Decision Tree Regressor unscaled")
            print("Best model:",best_params_p2)
            print("Mean squared error",mean_squared_error(Y_train_p2, Y_pred_p2))
            print("-----------------\n")
            
            plt.plot(Y_train_p2.to_numpy())
            plt.plot(Y_pred_p2)
            plt.legend(['Y', 'Y pred raw'], loc=4)
            plt.show()
            
         
    #2. Support vactor regressor
    elif classifier == "SupportVactorRegressor":
        
        if scaled == True:
            #CREATING TEST AND TRAIN SET
            X_train_p2 = input_variables
            Y_train_p2 = output_variables
            svr = SVR()
            param_grid={'kernel':['rbf','linear'],'C':[0.1,0.001],'gamma': [0.1,0.01],'max_iter':[100,1000]}
            gs_scaled_p2_svr=GridSearchCV(svr ,param_grid, cv=3)
            gs_scaled_p2_svr.fit(X_train_scaled_p2, Y_train_p2);
            Y_pred_svr = cross_val_predict(gs_scaled_p2_svr, X_train_scaled_p2, Y_train_p2, cv=3)
            best_params_svr=gs_scaled_p2_svr.best_params_
            accuracy_svr=gs_scaled_p2_svr.best_score_

            print("Support Vactor Regressor scaled")
            print("Best model:",best_params_svr)
            #print("Accuracy",round(accuracy_svr*100,3),"%")
            print("Mean squared error",mean_squared_error(Y_train_p2, Y_pred_svr))
            print("-----------------\n")

            plt.plot(Y_train_p2.to_numpy())
            plt.plot(Y_pred_svr)
            plt.legend(['Y', 'Y pred svr'], loc=4)
            plt.show()
         
        else:
            print("Pass scaled values!!!")
    else:
        print("Please pass given paramenetrs")


runPartTwo("DecisionTreeRegressor",input_variables,output_variables,False) #PASSING RAW VALUE WITHOUT SCALED

Explanation¶

Decision Tree Regressor¶

    1. max_depth = create nodes
    2. creation = gets the index value
    3. min_sample_leaf= minimun leaf on each node

Support Vactor Regressor¶

    1. kernel = mathematical function wheather we use polynomial, linear or rbf
    2. C = Regularization parameter
    3. gamma = Kernel coefficient 
    4. max_iter = iteration while running the model
  1. We have passed 'kernel':['rbf','linear'],'C':[0.1,0.001],'gamma': [0.1,0.01],'max_iter':[100,1000] in our model for Support Vactor Regressor.
  2. For Decision Tree Regressor we have passed 'max_depth': [2, 3, 4],'criterion':['mse'],'min_samples_leaf': [2, 3,4] as the hyperparamater.
  3. GrideSearchCV provides the best hyperparameters which generates the best output by using best_params_ 4.The mean square error of scaled and the unscaled Decision Tree Regressor are almost the same.
  4. Support Vactor Regressor is havinbg the highest Mean Square Error.

After scaling we are getting almost the same Mean Squared Error for both the Decision Tree Regressor models scaled and unscaled. This means our unscaled has less randomness within data points and good euclidean distance, that is why Mean Squared Error for both the models(unscaled features, scaled features) are almost the same. On the other hand the Mean Squared Error for the Support vactor regressor is the higgest which we can see in the third graph below. The predicted result by the Support vactor regressor diviate much with the true Y value i.e Y_pred_p2 in this case.
